And 2) the issue asks how drone technologies transform the human sensorium and bring about new, more than-human sensorial practices.

The issue brings into dialogue two aesthetic domains. 1) It refers to questions about how drone technology is mobilized and reimagined in artistic works, and the kinds of embodied experiences and socio-political imaginaries that are made sensible and possible by these works.

Delightful to bring this special issue on the "The Sensorial Experience of the Drone" into the world. It was a pleasure to edit Svea Braeunert, Rasmus Gahrn-Andersen, @dissemination, @yascoh, Rikke Munck Petersen, Andreas Graae and Maximilian Jablonowski. https://t.co/ak1oH25OR3

We are grateful to the authors for trusting us to edit their amazing work within this special issue, and we're very pleased to see this constellation of scholarship and practices coming together. Please enjoy the issue and share widely! 13/14

The issue concludes with an essay by visual artists Annarosa Kr√∏yer Holm and Miriam Haile, co-runners of the Hvid[me] Archive, an artistic research project highlighting critical, intersectional and decolonial practices.12/14

In her mixed-media essay, Lene Asp documents a field trip to Ghana with written and aural impressions to approach the landscape as a material archive and to explore how ‚Äúknowledge of history might be stored in other-than-text narratives‚Äù. 11/14

The Copenhagen-based decolonial feminist collective Marronage offers an intervention into a Danish history book which discusses the 1878 Fireburn labor revolt on St. Croix. Marronage‚Äôs intervention employs the practice of redaction and annotation to read and see otherwise.10/14

Historian @EtheleneW draws on the method of curatorial dreaming to explore how an imaginary exhibition can offer an alternative infrastructure to engage archival materials from her book "Searching for Utopia: African Americans in 20th Century Denmark". 9/14

Visual essay by Ghanaian artist Dorothy Amenuke  explores the politics of space and 'the possibly communicative potential of fibres and fabrics'. Amenuke questions who is allowed to inhabit which spaces and creates fabric installations as modes of inhabitation and intimacy.8/14

Archeologist Ayana Flewellen investigates the potentiality of archival and archaeological sources for accounting for the lived experiences of Afro-Crucians under Danish colonial rule through preliminary findings from her  archeological work at the Estate Little Princess.7/14

Visual artist Jeannette Ehlers contributes with documentation of her performance FOR LOVE ALONE, inspired by the four rebel queens of the Fireburn revolt. The documentation includes photos, video and a monologue written by novelist and poet @tiphanieyanique. 6/14

Visual artist @belleonblast reflects on the transatlantic dialogue behind the sculpture I Am Queen Mary (2018), co-created with Jeannette Ehlers. Belle‚Äôs proposition is to ‚Äúlower the gaze‚Äù and engage with the sculpture from the viewpoint of its coral stone base. 5/14

Issue begins w an essay by @belleonblast, Tami Navarro, @HadiyaSewer & @tiphanieyanique on the prison records of the four rebel queens of the Fireburn labour revolt, confronting the tensions between historical documentation and the islands collective memory of the four women.4/14

In our introduction, we reflect on the politics of digitization of the Danish colonial archives; we discuss notions of digital rematerialisation; and we expand existing concepts of infrastructure towards imaginative, creative and transgressive sharing practices. 3/14

Taking the digitization of the Danish colonial archives as a starting point, the issue features articles, essays and art projects addressing the  materialities of the archival record, while pointing to the need to reimagine infrastructures to share digitized heritage. 2/14

Much more work is needed to critically challenge gendered, sexualised and racialized norms of truth-telling that determine not only what can be said but also who can speak and how they may speak. We look forward to engaging in conversations that take this work further. 8

Beyond truth-telling, what this means for organizations, and societies more broadly, is that infrastructures matter because they fundamentally determine whose knowledge and labour are valued, and which subjectivities, bodies and voices come to count in social and public life.7/8
Moreover, we suggest that these leaky platforms reinforce gendered and sexualised norms of truth-telling, exposing female-identifying subjects to new vulnerabilities and discredit. 6/8

Through an analysis of the Facebook-Cambridge Analytica case, we contend that the leak is more than a system failure: it has been adopted as a business model by social media platforms, and has thus become an endemic mode of connective infrastructuring in digital communication.5/8

Focusing on whistleblowers such as Reality Winner, Chelsea Manning, Christopher Wylie and Brittany Kaiser, we demonstrate how whistleblowing and hacking are socially constructed and perceived as volitional gestures, while leaking is viewed as a passive failure of containment.4/8

Drawing on feminist infrastructure and media studies, we show how how digital infrastructures are overdetermined as leaky, passive and feminine in ways that not only devalue truth-telling acts by female-identifying subjects, but also subject them to risk and injustice. 3/8

We examine how truth-telling is gendered and how this determines who counts - and who doesn‚Äôt - as a truth-teller within digitally networked societies. We also argue that the gendering of truth-telling is shaped by how digital infrastructures themselves are gendered. 2/8

@kanarinka @_annie_ring @NThylstrup @KristinVeel We home in on the politics of such uncertainties and we highlight several arts-based projects that provide valuable contributions to understanding the unknowns, errors, and vulnerabilities implied by big data archives.

@kanarinka @_annie_ring @NThylstrup @KristinVeel Drawing on feminist, queer and critical race theories of the archive, we argue that big data, while technologically new, in fact belong in a long historical trajectory, one that is haunted by historical and contemporary uncertainties familiar from critiques of archival reason.

@kanarinka @_annie_ring @NThylstrup @KristinVeel The article outlines the conceptual and theoretical framework of the Uncertain Archives research collective and offers a preview into our forthcoming glossary of critical terms relevant to the conceptualisation and analysis of big data phenomena.
